    <stitle>DT-466E and 530E Diesel Engine Service (1995 through 1999) - SECTION 10: WATER PUMP AND THERMOSTAT -
        THERMOSTAT - INSPECTION
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="4">
        <title>INSPECTION</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect thermostat for cracks and pitting.</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>WHEN SERVICING THERMOSTAT, IT IS ESSENTIAL THAT THERMOSTAT OPENS FULLY AT SPECIFIED
                        TEMPERATURE TO AVOID AN OVERHEATING CONDITION WHICH MAY CAUSE ENGINE DAMAGE.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>ONLY GENUINE INTERNATIONAL(r) THERMO-STATS assure proper coolant flow and positive sealing
                        characteristics required to provide proper engine cooling.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check thermostat operation as follows, (
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1601009">10.9</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ):
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>EXERCISE CAUTION AND GOOD JUDGMENT TO AVOID INJURY WHEN DEALING WITH HOT WATER AND OBJECTS
                        DURING THERMOSTAT OPERATION CHECK. USE HEAT RESISTANT GLOVES AND WEAR APPROPRIATE EYE
                        PROTECTION.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Manually open thermostat enough to insert a nylon ribbon under valve seat. Suspend
                    thermostat in container so thermostat does not touch bottom of container.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Heat container filled with water to
                    <emph type="bold">"START-TO-OPEN</emph>" temperature of thermostat 82.2&#176; 0/2.8&#176;C (180&#176;
                    0/+5&#176; F). Observe thermometer and record temperature as soon as thermostat drops from nylon
                    ribbon.
                    <emph type="bold">THIS IS THE "START-TO-OPEN" TEMPERATURE.</emph>
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1601007" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5140" filename="../figeg5/EG5140.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 10.7 Remove Thermostat Mounting Bolts</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1601008" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5141" filename="../figeg5/EG5141.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 10.8 Remove Thermostat</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1601009" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg2387" filename="../figeg2/EG2387.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 10.9 Testing Thermostat</caption>
                </figure>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Continue to heat water to
                    <emph type="bold">"FULL-OPEN</emph>" temperature of thermostat 202&#176; F (94.4&#176; C). Observe
                    thermometer and movement of thermostat. Observe thermostat movement when
                    <emph type="bold">"FULL-OPEN</emph>" temperature is achieved. Minimum travel at "
                    <emph type="bold">FULL- OPEN"</emph>
                    temperature is 9.0 mm (.410 inches). Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1601010">10.10</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>BE SURE TO WEAR PROTECTIVE CLOTHING WHEN RETRIEVING THERMOSTAT FROM BOILING HOT WATER
                            CONTAINER.
                        </para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Remove thermostat from water, inspect seat area for pitting and foreign deposits.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Replace thermostat if it does not operate as described or meet visual inspection
                    criteria.
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1601010" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg2386" filename="../figeg2/EG2386.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 10.10 Thermostat Open/Closed Position</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">1. Thermostat</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">2. Maximum Travel 19.23mm(0.757 in.)</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">3. Closed Dimension 29.64mm (1.167 in.)</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">4. Minimum Travel 10.41mm (0.410 in)</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Visually inspect thermostat for the following conditions, which may cause improper closure:
                Replace as required.
            </para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Debris or loose fit at seat.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Rough or uneven wear at seal seat location.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Uneven seat.</para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
